[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Jones is a 77-year-old woman who presents to the GI Neoplasia Clinic for colon adenocarcinoma that was recently-diagnosed.  She had her annual general medical exam in April of 2010 at which point she was noted to be anemic with a hemoglobin of 10.6.  At that time she did not have any symptoms, and a colonoscopy was recommended.  This study, per report, only demonstrated diverticulosis.  She subsequently underwent a hematology evaluation which included ferritin levels that were normal and a bone marrow biopsy that was unrevealing and was recommended to have a six-month followup.  At the beginning of this month on September 1 she developed bright-red blood per rectum.  This lasted for a couple days, so she returned to her outpatient provider.  Due to this symptom she was admitted to the hospital.  Her hemoglobin remained unchanged at 10.5.  She underwent a repeat colonoscopy the following day on September 3.  This demonstrated a large colon mass in the distal transverse colon that was estimated to be 6 to 8-cm in size.  There were ulcerations, and the mucosa was noted to be friable.  This area was tattooed, and multiple biopsies were taken that demonstrated well-differentiated adenocarcinoma with infiltration into the stroma.  A CT-scan of the abdomen done the following day demonstrated this mass but did not demonstrate any synchronous lesions or lymphadenopathy.  The radiologist did comment on gastric wall thickening, and on our review it appears that there is a lesion in the spleen.  Her bleeding symptoms stopped approximately three days later.  She continues to have minimal symptoms, denying any abdominal pain, change in appetite.  She has had an intentional 5-pound weight-loss over the last two-months.  Over the last three days, she has noticed that her stool caliber has been narrowed but prior to this was not having any difficulties with constipation or diarrhea.
She does have a significant cardiac history.  She underwent a four-vessel CABG in 1997.  Since that time, she denies any recurrent episodes of chest pain.  She has had aortic stenosis which has been known for some time.  During her recent hospitalization a repeat echocardiogram was done, and by the outside reports, the gradient was over 40 mm Hg.  She was seen by one of the local cardiologists who suggested a coronary catheterization preoperatively.  Due to the slow pace of scheduling this, she presented to Goulds Hospital for further evaluation.  Her functional status is limited in large part due to osteoarthritis.  She reports she is able to walk two-to-three blocks at a slow-to-moderate pace but does have a fair amount of shortness-of-breath with this.  She previously had been on aspirin but stopped taking this following the recent onset of her GI bleeding.

[end section id="20103"]

